@rohanpaul_ai this chunking approach is brilliant for context optimization

when documents exceed context windows, equal chunks with overlap prevent information loss at boundaries

similar strategy works for complex workflows - break into digestible pieces that maintain context continuity

@rohanpaul_ai Long contracts overwhelm LLMs, context breaks, answers scatter.
LAMs flip the script. With @GetActionModel, you don‚Äôt just read a contract, you act on it: scroll, search, extract, cross-reference, and highlight clauses in real time.
The result: grounded, auditable answers

@geoffreylitt @YiningCao3 @peilingjiang @HaijunXia can that structure be an mcp? 

a model that takes bunch of mcps and builds upon them. 

or a model that sees the requests bunch of web apps make and learns how they behave and then builds an app that unifies all of that.

@ludwigABAP There are yeah, the issue is companies that know the verifiers for a specific industry have been struggling with the prompting LLM side.

The guys who are deep in on LLMs to manipulate them don‚Äôt have enough industry knowledge to do the verifiers.

This is just now being fixed.

@rohanpaul_ai Fantastic work from ByteDance, training agents to handle long, noisy, multi-step tasks with RL.
This is exactly why LAMs matter: models that act, see results, and adapt instead of just predicting tokens.
With @GetActionModel, execution > conversation. Agents that finish the job.

@iamtrask Thanks, this lands. Fair to say LLMs interpolate inside a learned manifold and hallucinate near or beyond its boundary? 

If so, the goal is less adding ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know‚Äù and more detecting the boundary and then choosing to abstain, retrieve, or route to tools. 

What do you think?

@quantscience_ Multi-agent trading is a strong example of why execution > text.
LAMs extend this idea beyond finance, real-world workflows, actions, and automation all coordinated by agents.
Excited to see more open-source energy here.
@getactionmodel #LAM

@rohanpaul_ai This also allows agents tasked with stopping inconvenient truths from being shown. 

It will just not return. 

This is called planting an excuse on public. ‚Ä¢

@rohanpaul_ai This magic line added to the prompt minimizes halucinations to almost zero:
"Never guess the answer. Ask the user for more info or explain that you don't know the answer."

Just allow LLM to admit it doesn't know and never imagine answers.

@rohanpaul_ai Guess?

Nah, there is literally zero guessing going on with LLMs. Its search. Its scraping the internet and giving you the result you want to hear

Soon people will realize this, and the AI companies will be sued out of existence for violating copyright and we can finally move on

@rohanpaul_ai No shit.
Say grpo, you want the model to guess, and maybe get something right 2 times over 100 sampeled answers so that your rewardfunction can reinforce that. 
Imagine getting 100x "I dont know" and a reward of 0.

@connordavis_ai Love this modular approach

SLMs by default, fallback to LLMs only when needed.

Cleaner, faster, cheaper.

